 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are tasked with classifying a user's query related to banking or financial app operations into one of several predefined categories. Carefully analyze the user's message and assign exactly one category that most accurately and specifically matches the described issue, question, or request.\n\nKey domain-specific rules and guidelines:\n\n1. Use only the predefined categories as output. Each user's message must be classified into exactly one—no more, no less.\n2. Output only the single category name. Do not include explanations, additional text, or formatting.\n3. Always select the category that directly and specifically matches the explicit operation or issue described in the user's message. Do not generalize, infer, or guess beyond what is directly stated.\n4. If the user mentions a specific operation, always prefer the most precise corresponding category, even if broader categories might plausibly fit.\n5. Some examples of domain-specific mappings and clarifications:\n   - If a user’s message is about accessing their PIN or questions related to their physical card features (such as PIN delivery), choose “get_physical_card” rather than more general identity or access categories.\n   - “Balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer” is correct only when the user explicitly mentions a bank transfer and a balance update issue. Do not use for general missing funds or top-up delays unless “bank transfer” is directly mentioned.\n   - Use “pending_top_up” only if the user states a top-up (any method) is in progress, processing, or awaiting completion.\n   - If a transfer failed completely, use “failed_transfer.” If it’s still processing, select “pending_transfer.”\n   - “Exchange_via_app” is exclusively for queries or issues about converting or exchanging currencies within the app.\n   - “Receiving_money” should be used for messages about receiving funds into the account (like salary or transfer), especially when the query is about process, eligibility, or currency handling.\n   - For issues about physical card delivery or usage (including PIN inquiries), use “get_physical_card.”\n6. Do not infer user intent or additional context not explicitly stated; strictly rely on the text provided.\n7. If a message could fit two or more categories, choose the most specific and directly related one.\n\nInput format:\n- You will receive a plain text user message as “text”.\n\nOutput format:\n- Respond with the single most specific applicable category label, exactly as provided in the category list, and nothing else.\n\nYour categories are as follows (use exactly as written; no deviations, casing changes, or extra labels): automatic_top_up, balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer, beneficiary_not_allowed, cancel_transfer, card_payment_fee_charged, card_payment_not_recognised, declined_cash_withdrawal, exchange_rate, exchange_via_app, failed_transfer, get_disposable_virtual_card, get_physical_card, passcode_forgotten, pending_top_up, pending_transfer, receiving_money, reverted_card_payment?, top_up_by_cash_or_cheque, top_up_reverted, topping_up_by_card, transfer_fee_charged, transfer_into_account, transfer_timing, verify_my_identity, verify_source_of_funds.\n\nCarefully read each user message and apply these rules and mappings for precise, domain-appropriate classification."
